  "theory": "Pipelining is a technique used in computer architecture to improve the throughput of instruction execution by overlapping the execution phases of multiple instructions simultaneously. It is analogous to an assembly line in a factory.\n\nThe 5 Pipeline Stages:\n1. IF — Instruction Fetch: The Program Counter (PC) is used to fetch the next instruction from memory into the Instruction Register (IR). The PC is then incremented to point to the next instruction.\n2. ID — Instruction Decode: The fetched instruction is decoded. The Control Unit generates control signals. Register operands are read from the Register File simultaneously.\n3. EX — Execute: The ALU performs the required arithmetic or logical operation. For memory instructions, the effective memory address is computed (base + offset).\n4. MEM — Memory Access: For LOAD instructions, data is read from the Data Memory. For STORE instructions, data is written to Data Memory. For non-memory instructions, this stage passes results through.\n5. WB — Write Back: The result of the ALU operation or the data read from memory is written back to the destination register in the Register File.\n\nPipeline Throughput Analysis:\n- Without pipelining (sequential): n instructions × k stages = n×k clock cycles.\n- With pipelining: k + (n-1) clock cycles (fill time + remaining instructions).\n- Speedup = (n × k) / (k + n - 1) ≈ k (ideal) for large n.\n- For 7 instructions, 5 stages: Pipelined = 5 + 6 = 11 cycles. Sequential = 35 cycles. Speedup ≈ 3.18×.\n\nKey Observation (Staircase Pattern):\nEach instruction starts its IF stage exactly 1 clock cycle after the previous instruction. This creates the diagonal staircase pattern visible in the diagram. At clock cycle 5, all 5 pipeline stages are simultaneously active with different instructions — this is 'full pipeline utilization'.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "5 stages: IF (Instruction Fetch) → ID (Decode) → EX (Execute) → MEM (Memory) → WB (Write Back).",
    "Each stage takes exactly 1 clock cycle; clock cycle time = slowest stage time.",
    "7 instructions with 5 stages require 5 + (7-1) = 11 cycles instead of 35 — a 3.18× speedup.",
    "Pipeline is 'full' (all stages active) from clock cycle 5 onward.",
    "General formula: Total cycles = k + (n-1), where k = number of stages, n = number of instructions.",
    "Pipeline hazards (data, control, structural) can stall the pipeline, reducing actual speedup."
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "RISC processor design (MIPS, ARM, RISC-V) — all use 5-stage pipelines.",
    "Throughput analysis and CPI (Cycles Per Instruction) calculation in exams.",
    "Comparing pipelined vs. non-pipelined processor performance."
  ]
